{"cursor":"21077","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nA 'rumor' or 'rumour' (spelling differs between American and British English) is\noften viewed as \"an unverified account or explanation of events circulating from\nperson to person and pertaining to an object, event, or issue in public concern\"\n(33) {{Cite journal\n  | last1 = Peterson | first1 = Warren last2 = Gist | first2 = Noel title =\n  | Rumor and Public Opinion journal = The American Journal of Sociology volume\n  | = 57 issue = 2 pages = 159â167 date = September 1951 year = 1951 doi =\n  | 10.1086/220916 author = Peterson, Warren A. jstor=2772077}} However, a\n  | review of the research on rumor conducted by Pendleton in 1998 found that\n  | research across sociology, psychology, and communication studies had widely\n  | varying definitions of rumor. Pendleton, S.c. (1998), 'Rumor research\n  | revisited and expanded', Language&\nCommunication, vol. 1. no. 18, pp. 69-86. \n\nThus, rumor is a concept that lacks a particular definition in the social\nsciences. But most theories agree that rumor involves some kind of a statement\nwhose veracity is not quickly or ever confirmed. In addition, some scholars have\nidentified rumor as a subset of propaganda, the latter another notoriously\ndifficult concept to define. A pioneer of propaganda studies, Harold Lasswell\ndefined propaganda in 1927 as referring \"solely to the control of opinion by\nsignificant symbols, or, to speak more concretely and less accurately, by\nstories, rumors, reports, pictures, and other forms of social communication\"\n(1927:9). Propaganda Technique in the World War (1927; Reprinted with a new\nintroduction, 1971)\n\nRumors are also often discussed with regard to \"misinformation\" and\n\"disinformation\" (the former often seen as simply false and the latter seen as\ndeliberately false, though usually from a government source given to the media\nor a foreign government). from Oxford English Dictionary, 2nd ed.,\n1